FAQs
Is it expensive to study in Latvia?

Tuition fees in Latvia vary depending on the university and program. On average, tuition fees for international students range from 2,000 to 8,000 euros per year for bachelor's programs and from 2,500 to 10,000 euros per year for master's programs. Living costs are also relatively affordable, with an average monthly expense of around 400 to 700 euros for accommodation, food, transportation, and other expenses.
Do I need to speak Latvian to study in Latvia?

While some programs in Latvia are taught in Latvian, many universities offer programs taught in English for international students. If you choose to study in a program taught in Latvian, you may be required to demonstrate proficiency in the language. However, for programs taught in English, proficiency in Latvian is not required.
Are there scholarship opportunities for international students in Latvia?

Yes, there are scholarship opportunities for international students to study in Latvia. The Latvian government offers scholarships through the State Education Development Agency, which cover full tuition fees and provide a monthly stipend for living expenses. Additionally, many Latvian universities offer scholarships based on academic merit, financial need, or other criteria. It's advisable to check with your chosen university or the State Education Development Agency for specific scholarship opportunities.
Can I work while study in Latvia?

Yes, international students in Latvia are allowed to work part-time while studying. Students from EU/EEA countries do not need a work permit to work in Latvia, while students from non-EU/EEA countries are permitted to work up to 20 hours per week during the academic year and full-time during holidays. However, it's important to note that income from part-time work may not be sufficient to cover all expenses, so it's advisable to have additional financial support.
